Distributions

Lets denote the number of candidates as mm.

Let GTGT be the ground-truth ranking of the mm candidates.

The probability of sampling a ranking vector riri is defined as follows: Pϵ(ri)=1Dist(GT,ri)+ε⋅CPϵ(ri)=1Dist(GT,ri)+ε⋅C Where CC is a normalization constant and εε is a small constant to avoid division by 0. CC is defined as follows: C=1∑m!j=11Dist(GT,rj)+εC=1∑m!j=11Dist(GT,rj)+ε

class Distribution1:
    def __init__(self, gt, epsilon=1, norm_order=None):
        self.gt = np.array(gt)
        self.norm_order = norm_order
        self.number_of_candidates = len(self.gt)
        self.epsilon = epsilon
        self.c = self.compute_norm()

    def compute_distance(self, ri):
        if np.array_equal(self.gt, np.array(ri)):
            return 0
        return norm(self.gt - np.array(ri),  ord=self.norm_order)
    
    def compute_norm(self):
        all_permutations = list(permutations(self.gt))
        sum_of_inverse_dist = sum([1/(self.compute_distance(ri) + self.epsilon) for ri in all_permutations])
        return 1/sum_of_inverse_dist
    
    def probability(self, ri):
        return (1 / (self.compute_distance(ri) + self.epsilon)) * self.c

Dist. 2 - Inverse Distance Epsilon Family

Lets denote the number of candidates as $m$.

Let $GT$ be the ground-truth ranking of the $m$ candidates.

The probability of sampling a ranking vector $r_i$ is defined as follows: $$\mathbb{P}(r_i) = C - \frac{Dist(GT, r_i)}{\sum_{j=1}^{m!}Dist(GT, r_j) } $$ Where $C$ is a normalization constant and it's defined as follows: $$C = \frac{2}{m!}$$

class Distribution2:
    def __init__(self, gt, norm_order=None):
        self.gt = np.array(gt)
        self.norm_order = norm_order
        self.number_of_candidates = len(self.gt)
        self.c = self.compute_norm()
        self.sum_distances = sum([self.compute_distance(ri) for ri in list(permutations(self.gt))])
       

    def compute_distance(self, ri):
        if np.array_equal(self.gt, np.array(ri)):
            return 0
        return norm(self.gt - np.array(ri), ord=self.norm_order)
    
    def compute_norm(self):
        return 2/(factorial(self.number_of_candidates))
    
    def probability(self, ri):
        return self.c - self.compute_distance(ri)/self.sum_distances

Create Datasets Based On The Distributions

We will create datasets based on sampling from some distributions. The parameters of those distributions will be as the following parameters:

  • $m \in [3, 5 ] $
  • $n = 1000000$
  • $\text{Distance function} \in [\text{Euclidean}, \text{Manhattan}, \text{Infinty}] $
  • For Dist1:
    • $\varepsilon \in [2, 5, 10 ] $
def generate_dataset(dist_num, distance_function, norm_order, m, epsilon=None, n=1000000):

    name = f"data_distribution_{dist_num}_dist_{distance_function}_m_{m}_n_{n}"
    if dist_num == 1:
        name += f"_eps_{epsilon}"
        if os.path.exists(f"data/{name}.csv"):
            return
        gt = np.random.permutation([i+1 for i in range(0, m)])
        distribution = Distribution1(gt, epsilon=epsilon, norm_order=norm_order)
    elif dist_num == 2:
        if os.path.exists(f"data/{name}.csv"):
            return
        gt = np.random.permutation([i+1 for i in range(0, m)])
        distribution = Distribution2(gt, norm_order=norm_order)

    with open(f"data/gt_{name}.json", 'w') as json_file:
        json.dump(gt.tolist(), json_file)

    probs = {}
    # distances = {}
    for p in list(permutations(gt)):
        probs[p] = distribution.probability(p)
        # distances[p] = distribution.compute_distance(p)
        
    keys_list = [str(key) for key in list(probs.keys())]
    values_list = list(probs.values())

    samples = {i + 1 :eval(np.random.choice(keys_list, p=values_list)) for i in range(n)}
    df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(samples, orient='index',  columns=[f"{i + 1}" for i in range(len(gt))])
    df.index.name = 'index'

    df.to_csv(f"data/{name}.csv")
# Generate datasets of 1,000,000 rankings based on dofferent distributions

Sampling and Convergence

    This part consists of th e following sections:

  • Plot samples histogram: Plot histogram of the generated datasets. We would expect the samples to follow the $d-monotonic$ distribution.

  • Plot convergence of different rankers: For the generated datasets show the convergance of the probabilty of choosing the GT as a function of sample size. We will compare the different induced distributions and different rankers - Modal ranker, Borda ranker, and Plurality ranker.

Plot samples histogram

def plot_samples_hist(df,gt, dist_metric):
    # histogram of the sampled permutations
    labels = df.apply(lambda x: str(x.values), axis=1).values
    df['labels'] = labels
    value_counts = df["labels"].value_counts()
    
    # Plot the histogram
    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 3))  # set the figure size
    # set fontsize to 8
    plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 6})
    plt.bar(value_counts.index, value_counts.values, color='skyblue')
    gt_col = str(gt.T.values[0])
    plt.axvline(x=gt_col, color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)
    plt.xticks(rotation='vertical')
    plt.xlabel('Permutations')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title(f'Histogram of sampled permutations sorted by {dist_metric} distance from GT' + gt_col )
    plt.tight_layout()  # adjusts subplot params so that the subplot fits in to the figure area
    plt.show()

Plot convergence of different rankers

    In this part we used the following rankers:

  • Modal Ranker: Given a collection of input rankings, the modal ranking rule simply selects the most frequent ranking as the output.

  • Borda Ranker:Given a collection of input rankings, the Borda score of each candidate will be calculated and the sorted scores would induce a ranking.

  • Plurality Ranker:Given a collection of input rankings, the Plurality score of each candidate will be calculated and those scores would induce a ranking.
def modal_ranker(df):
    return df['labels'].value_counts().index[0]
def borda_ranker(df):
    # sum for each candidate his borda score
    candidates = {int(candidate): 0 for candidate in df.columns if candidate != 'labels'}
    m = len(candidates)
    for vote in df.values:
        for i, candidate in enumerate(vote):
            if candidate not in candidates.keys():
                continue
            candidates[candidate] += m - i
    #return the ordered candidates by their borda score as string of list
    df = pd.DataFrame(sorted(candidates.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True))
    return str(df[0].values)
def plurality_ranker(df):
    candidates = {int(candidate): 0 for candidate in df.columns if candidate != 'labels'}
    m = len(candidates)
    for vote in df.values:
        candidates[vote[0]] += 1  
    #return the ordered candidates by their borda score as string of list
    df = pd.DataFrame(sorted(candidates.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True))
    return str(df[0].values)
def approximate_ranker_probability(df: pd.DataFrame, gt:str , ranker: callable, sample_size: int, num_iterations: int = 1000):
    results = np.zeros(num_iterations)
    for i in range(num_iterations):
        sample = df.sample(sample_size)
        chosen_rank = ranker(sample)
        if chosen_rank == gt:
            results[i] = 1
    return results.mean(), results.std(ddof=1)/np.sqrt(num_iterations)
def plot_convergence(args):
    df, gt,label, ranker, sample_sizes, num_iterations = args
    results = []
    for sample_size in sample_sizes:
        results.append(approximate_ranker_probability(df, gt, ranker, sample_size, num_iterations))
    # plot convergence line with error bars
    plt.errorbar(sample_sizes, [r[0] for r in results], yerr=[r[1] for r in results], fmt='-o',label=label, alpha=0.5)
def plot_convergence_comparison(dfs, gts,labels, ranker, sample_sizes, title="", num_iterations = 1000):
    args = [(df, gt, label, ranker,sample_sizes,num_iterations) for df, gt, label in zip(dfs, gts, labels)]
    for arg in args:
        plot_convergence(arg)
    plt.xlabel('Sample Size')
    plt.ylabel('Probability of Choosing GT')
    plt.title('Convergence of the Ranker ' + ranker.__name__ + " " + title)
    plt.legend()
    plt.axhline(y=1, color='r', linestyle='--')
    plt.show()
def plot_convergence_comparison_rankers(df, label, gt, rankers, sample_sizes, title = "", num_iterations = 1000):
    args = [(df, gt, str(ranker.__name__), ranker,sample_sizes,num_iterations) for ranker in rankers]
    for arg in args:
        plot_convergence(arg)
    plt.xlabel('Sample Size')
    plt.ylabel('Probability of Choosing GT')
    plt.title(f'Convergence of Rankers for dataset {label} {title}')
    plt.legend()
    plt.axhline(y=1, color='r', linestyle='--')
    plt.show()

The following graphs show the convergence of the probability of choosing the GT. We sampled a subset of the data and applied the rankers. We calculated the empirical probability and confidance interval of 95%

For the Modal Ranking, we showed that the CI is getting smaller when more iteration of sampling is being held.

Real Data Analysis

I this part we used real world data from kaggle. We used "Video Games on Metacritic.com". This Dataset containes scores of video games given by different people/organizations. We used the modal ranker to show its application s on real world data.

Data Preprocessing

For each console, we chose its top 5 games. Then, we found the console with the largest number of voters for those 5 games.

m = 5
most_voters = 0
console_name = None
selected_games = []
for f in os.listdir('data'):
    if "score" not in f:
        continue
    df = pd.read_csv('data/' + f, index_col=0)
    votes_for_each_game = df.T
    # Top m games
    good_names = [name for name in votes_for_each_game.count().sort_values(ascending=False)[:m].index]
    df = votes_for_each_game[good_names].T
    number_of_full_voting = len([voter for voter, num_votes in df.count().sort_values(ascending=False).items() if num_votes == m])
    if most_voters < number_of_full_voting:
        console_name = f
        most_voters = number_of_full_voting
        selected_games = good_names

print(f" Console name - {console_name.split('_')[1]}\n",
      f"Number of voters that voted for all {m} games: {most_voters}")

bad_cols = []
for col in selected_df.columns:
    if len(selected_df[col].value_counts()) <= 3:
        bad_cols.append(col)
    # check that all values are numbers
    elif len(selected_df[pd.to_numeric(selected_df[col], errors='coerce').notnull()]) != len(selected_df):
        bad_cols.append(col)
    else:
        selected_df[col] = selected_df[col].astype(float)

selected_df = selected_df.drop(columns=bad_cols)
selected_df = selected_df.astype(float)
print(f"Number of voters that voted for all {m} games after filtering: {len(selected_df.columns)}")

# For each voter, rank the games. If there is a tie, between two games, break it by lexical order of the games.
for voter in selected_df.columns:
    selected_df[voter] = selected_df[voter].rank(ascending=False, method='first')

selected_df.T.to_csv('data/' + console_name.split("_")[1] + "_ranking.csv", index=True)
Number of voters that voted for all 5 games after filtering: 49

After we filtered out the bad records, the data contained scores from 49 rankers.

Finding GT using the Metascore

We used the total scoring, that was calculated based on all voters, to find the real rank of our games.

# Load the metadata and check the GT
summary_ps4 = pd.read_csv('data/01_ps4_details.csv', index_col=0).T[selected_games].T
gt = summary_ps4.Metascore.rank(ascending=False, method='first').values
print(f"The GT ranking is: {gt}")
The GT ranking is: [3. 5. 2. 1. 4.]

Ranking using the Modal Ranking, Borda Ranking, and Plurality Ranking

ranking = pd.read_csv('data/' + console_name.split("_")[1] + "_ranking.csv", index_col=0)
# change the columns names to [1,2,3,4,5]
# ranking.columns = [1,2,3,4,5]
ranking.columns = [1,2,3,4,5]
ranking['labels'] = ranking.apply(lambda x: str(x.values), axis=1)

print(f"The selected ranking based on Modal Ranking is: {ranking['labels'].value_counts().idxmax()}")
The selected ranking based on Modal Ranking is: [3. 5. 1. 2. 4.]
print(f"The Borda ranking is: {borda_ranker(ranking)}")
The Borda ranking is: [5 3 1 2 4]
print(f"The Plurality ranking is: {plurality_ranker(ranking)}")
The Plurality ranking is: [3 5 4 1 2]

As arrise from the results, the modal ranker was the closest to the GT. The ranking is a bit different from the GT but that can be explained by the small number of voters.
